Step 1

Reading in the data: Summary of findings:

There are 57,761 observations in the 2022 dataset, with 20 variables. There are 15976 observations in the 2002 dataset with 20 variables. Together in the combined dataset, there are 73,737 observations with the same 20 variables. From question 4, there were implausible observations found in the Daily Mean PM 2.5 Concentration variable, in which there were negative values. Because these observations are not possible, they were deleted from the dataset (in Question 4).

data1 <- data.table::fread("2022cali.csv")
data2 <- data.table::fread("2002cali.csv")

library(leaflet)
library(viridis)
Loading required package: viridisLite
data4 <- data3[!is.na(year)]
# Generating a color palette
year.pal <- colorFactor(viridis(7), data4$year)


map <- leaflet(data4) %>% 
  # The looks of the Map
  addProviderTiles('CartoDB.Positron') %>% 
  # Some circles
  addCircleMarkers(
    lat = ~latit, lng=~long, fillColor = ~year.pal(year),
    stroke=FALSE,
   fillOpacity = 1, 
    ) %>%
  # And a pretty legend
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=year.pal, values=data4$year,
          title='pm 2.5 across 20 years', opacity=1)
map

**used parts of stack overflow code to help with year.pal and other parts of code above

In general, the spatial distribution of sites from 2002 to 2022 has remained the same. There seems to be one site in 2002 that is no longer in 2022 that was not replaced by a site anywhere near the area. Besides this, there seems to be more sites in 2022 then there was in 2002, possibly allowing for better estimations of pm 2.5 levels.

There does not appear to be any missing values of pm 2.5 in the cleaned version of the dataset, which is what I was trying to accomplish in earlier steps. However, upon inspection of the minimum values of the pm 2.5 variable, there are negative values, which are implausible. Because these values do not make sense, I chose to omit them from the dataset. Temporally, it seems that the 2022 dataset contained the implausible values in the Daily Mean PM2.5 Concentration variable.

  # Some circles
  addCircleMarkers(
    lat = ~latit, lng=~long, fillColor = ~ID.pal(newsite),
    stroke=FALSE,
   fillOpacity = 1, 
    ) %>%
  # And a pretty legend

State level:

In the 2022 year, it seems that the daily mean pm 2.5 concentration was between 0-50, and much more spread out in 2022. However, there were much more observations in 2022 than in 2002 so visual interpretations are not adequate in determining comparisons between the two years. In the box plot with both years, you can visually see the data more spread out in the high ranges of pm2.5 concentrations compared to the 2002 year.

County level:

It is difficult to accurately compare counties in the combined years dataset due to the fact that there are so many counties to compare. Despite this, the colored bar graphâs side labels indicate the highest to lowest ranges of county pm 2.5 levels. Yolo, Ventura, Tulare, Trinity, and Tehama had the lowest pm2.5 levels, and Almeda, Butte, Calaveras, Colusa, and Contra Costa had the highest pm 2.5 levels.

Site levels in Los Angeles:

Based on the bar graph, there seems to be one site in particular that has the highest levels of pm2.5 compared to any other site. Although I cannot tell which site this is due to the clustering of all the sites, I can infer it to be Azusa after ordering the pm2.5 variable and viewing the greatest numberâs site. Additionally, the map confirms this. There is a valley in the sites with the hightest levels of pm2.5, possibly explaining why.
